liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: So, we get to the end of an extraordinary half of football. Spurs were rampant early on, but it's all gone wrong in a big way for Ange Postecoglou since then. Cristian Romero has been sent off, the other half of that excellent centre back partnership, Micky van de Ven, has gone off with a hamstring injury and key player James Maddison has gone off injured. But despite all that it's still 1-1, with both teams having goals ruled out by a forensic VAR that is investigating every little incident so far in this game. Two goals, three chalked off, a red card… It's been a wild one - and we're only half way through.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Half time, Spurs 1-1 Chelsea

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: If there's one lesson our new Reserve Bank governor hasn't gleaned from her predecessor, it is the danger of being overly precise. Michele Bullock has been adamant that taming inflation in a timely matter is a top priority. A fortnight ago, however, she added a dash of precision to the message. The RBA, she said, "would not hesitate" to lift rates again if there was a "material" change to the inflation forecasts. Lo and behold, when the September quarter inflation figures dropped, the numbers were hotter than the RBA's forecasts. That put a question mark over the bank's well-telegraphed plan to gradually bring inflation back to between 2 and 3 per cent by 2025. Many now argue that the material change clause that's been inserted into the dialogue looks to have been triggered and the RBA has little option but to follow through. For more, here's the latest analysis from business editor Ian Verrender :
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Why the Reserve Bank will probably lift interest rates on Melbourne Cup Day even though it doesn't need to

featuredLink.title: Candour and credibility: Has Michele Bullock backed herself into a corner?

children.content: If there's one lesson our new Reserve Bank governor hasn't gleaned from her predecessor, it is the danger of being overly precise.
Michele Bullock has been adamant that taming inflation in a timely matter is a top priority.
A fortnight ago, however, she added a dash of precision to the message. The RBA, she said, "would not hesitate" to lift rates again if there was a "material" change to the inflation forecasts.
Lo and behold, when the September quarter inflation figures dropped, the numbers were hotter than the RBA's forecasts.
That put a question mark over the bank's well-telegraphed plan to gradually bring inflation back to between 2 and 3 per cent by 2025.
Many now argue that the material change clause that's been inserted into the dialogue looks to have been triggered and the RBA has little option but to follow through.
For more, here's the latest analysis from business editor
Ian Verrender

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Ahead of this afternoon's decision by the RBA, here's a quick refresher of where the current cash rate sits. After leaving rates on hold at 4.1% since its June meeting, the cash rate is currently the highest it's been since April 2012. Should the RBA lift interest rates by 0.25 percentage points at 2:30pm AEDT, it would take the cash rate to 4.35%. That would make it the highest rate since November 2011 — which is a whopping 12 years ago, if you can believe it. (I personally can't...) Here's the history of the cash rate since 1990. As you can see, when we look at the data from more than 30 years, the recent rate hikes are incredibly steep compared to past increases.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: What does the current cash rate look like?

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Economists say an increase in interest rates is likely when the Reserve Bank board holds its monthly meeting today. Between May 2022 and June this year, the RBA have increased the cash rate to 4.1% — up from its record low level of 0.1% during the pandemic — but have held it steady since. Chief economist at HSBC, Paul Bloxham, says inflation has not been coming down as quickly as the central bank wants — which makes another rate rise necessary. "We think they will lift interest rates ... by 25 basis points," he said. "We also think that they ought to, that we need to lift interest rates, financial conditions need to be tightened further as inflation is still a primary challenge and it's still too high in Australia." Commsec market analyst, Laura Beserati, says inflation remains a concern. "We have been hearing a hiking bias from the new governor Michele Bullock, but interestingly according to market pricing its a 50-50 chance that it could go either way," she said. "Most analysts expect rates to go up and our view here at CBA is that interest rates will increase by 25 basis points." Brian Redican, chief economist at NSW Treasury Corporation (TCorp) says a rate hike by the RBA will hurt households already on the brink. "The Reserve Bank's own research suggests that somewhere between 5 and 15% of people with a mortgage are actually spending more than they're actually earning at the moment," he said. "Obviously that's not sustainable and how they react to another potential rate hike could potentially be quite extreme."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: What do economists think the RBA will do with rates?
